 Branded and Consumed -- t12. Self-Branding among Freelance Knowledge Workers -- t13. Consuming Work -- t14. Conclusion -- tAbout the Editors and Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAcross the world, workers labor without pay for the benefit of profitable businesses—and it's legal. Labor trends like outsourcing and technology hide some workers, and branding and employer mandates erase others. Invisible workers who remain under-protected by wage laws include retail workers who function as walking billboards and take payment in clothing discounts or prestige; waitstaff at “breastaurants” who conform their bodies to a business model; and inventory stockers at grocery stores who go hungry to complete their shifts. Invisible Labor gathers essays by prominent sociologists and legal scholars to illuminate how and why such labor has been hidden from view.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aLabor. 0aWork environment. 0aWork. 7aLAW / Labor & Employment.2bisacsh  aembodied labor.  aexploitation of labor.  aexploitative workplace.  ainvisible employees.  ainvisible labor.  ainvisible workers.  alabor and employment.  alabor saving technology.  alabor studies.  alabor.  amanipulative employment practices.  amanual labor.  anetworking.  aoutsourcing labor.  aprofessional labor.  asociology.  aunacknowledged labor.  aunacknowledged work effort.  aunacknowledged work product.  aunpaid job functions.  aunpaid labor.  aunpaid work.  awage and employment.  awork.  aworking class.  aworkplace activism.1 aArvidsson, Adam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAvery, Dianne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBandinelli, Car